The data appears to be cyclical rather than linear, therefore a moving average column will be made.

In [7]:
ConstDf['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
ConstDf['sqErr'] = np.NaN
# Chaging the DataFrame index to DatetimeIndex data type is required for using one of the functions below
ConstDf.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='m', start=pd.Timestamp(year=2002, month=1, day=31), periods = len(ConstDf['Month']))

window = 12
window = window - window % 2

for i in range(int(window/2),ConstDf.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
    ConstDf.loc[ConstDf.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*ConstDf.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Private Construction'] + ConstDf.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'].sum() + 0.5*ConstDf.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'])/float(window)

ConstDf['sqErr'] = (ConstDf['Private Construction'] - ConstDf['MovAvg'])**2
ConstDf.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)

R1 is found by subtracting the moving average from the actual private construction spending

R1 error is what percentage of private construction the moving average was off by

In [9]:

cycleLen = period
numCycles = int(len(ConstDf)/cycleLen + 0.5)
cycles = [ConstDf.iloc[range(i*period,min((i+1)*period,len(ConstDf)))]['R1'] for i in range(numCycles)]
ptsInCycles = [ConstDf.iloc[range(i,len(ConstDf['R1']),period)]['R1'].tolist() for i in range(period)]
avg = [sum(pts)/len(pts) for pts in ptsInCycles]

A value for the cyclicality is computed and then plotted alongside $R1$

In [14]:
cycleLen = period   
numCycles = int(len(ConstDf)/cycleLen + 0.5)
ConstDf['C'] = np.NaN   # Creates an empty column for the cyclicality component data
for i in range(len(ConstDf)):
    ConstDf.loc[ConstDf.index[i], 'C'] = avg[i % cycleLen] 

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(8,5)
ax.plot(ConstDf['C'],label='Cyclic Pattern')
ax.plot(ConstDf['R1'],label='Remainder After Trend')
ax.set_ylabel('Private Construction')
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
fig.legend()
plt.show()

The code cell below does these:

  • Computes the remaining residual construction spending to be explained, $R2$, after subtracting the cyclical component, $C \left( m \right)$: this is the $\epsilon \left( m \right)$ in our model.
  • Computes the error, $R2$, as a percentage of the demand time series.
  • Computes the mathematical model 'fit', composed of the trend and cyclical components: $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$.
  • Plots the fit of the model $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$ with the original data, $H \left( m \right)$.
  • Computes the average absolute error of $R2Error$ of the original demand time series.
  • Removes the sqErr column because it is no longer needed
In [15]:
ConstDf['R2'] = ConstDf['R1'] - ConstDf['C']
ConstDf['R2X'] = ConstDf['R2']/ConstDf['Private Construction']
ConstDf['R2Error'] = abs(ConstDf['R2']/ConstDf['Private Construction'])
ConstDf['R2ErrorX'] = ConstDf['R2Error']/ConstDf['Private Construction']
ConstDf['fit'] = ConstDf['MovAvg'] + ConstDf['C']
ConstDf.drop(['sqErr'],axis=1,inplace=True)
print('Average Error: ', sum(ConstDf['R2Error'])/len(ConstDf))
print(ConstDf)

The data appears to be cyclical rather than linear, therefore a moving average column will be made.

In [20]:
ConstDf['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
ConstDf['sqErr'] = np.NaN
# Chaging the DataFrame index to DatetimeIndex data type is required for using one of the functions below
ConstDf.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='m', start=pd.Timestamp(year=2002, month=1, day=31), periods = len(ConstDf['Month']))

window = 12
window = window - window % 2

for i in range(int(window/2),ConstDf.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
    ConstDf.loc[ConstDf.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*ConstDf.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Public Construction'] + ConstDf.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Public Construction'].sum() + 0.5*ConstDf.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Public Construction'])/float(window)

ConstDf['sqErr'] = (ConstDf['Public Construction'] - ConstDf['MovAvg'])**2
ConstDf.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)

The code cell below does these:

  • Computes the remaining residual construction spending to be explained, $R2$, after subtracting the cyclical component, $C \left( m \right)$: this is the $\epsilon \left( m \right)$ in our model.
  • Computes the error, $R2$, as a percentage of the demand time series.
  • Computes the mathematical model 'fit', composed of the trend and cyclical components: $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$.
  • Plots the fit of the model $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$ with the original data, $H \left( m \right)$.
  • Computes the average absolute error of $R2Error$ of the original demand time series.
  • Removes the sqErr column because it is no longer needed
